Pocock, 1895, by monotypy.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="181" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pocock" authorityYear="1895" class="Arachnida" family="Barychelidae" genus="Cyrtogrammomma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cyrtogrammomma" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Cyrtogrammomma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by the short distal article of the PLS; anterior eye row strongly procurved with the anterior lateral eyes on the carapace margin; lack of tibial apophysis and cymbium elongated on males and few cupules on labium (3-15 cupules). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pocock" authorityYear="1895" class="Arachnida" family="Barychelidae" genus="Cyrtogrammomma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cyrtogrammomma" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Cyrtogrammomma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Theraphosidae" genus="Trichopelma" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trichopelma" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Trichopelma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by short distal article of the PLS, male palpal bulb with pyriform aspect, and female spermatheca with two bilobed receptacles. The genus differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Theraphosidae" genus="Trichopelma" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trichopelma" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Trichopelma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the absence of booklung combs, lack of tibial apophysis, and male cymbium lobes strongly pronounced, retrolateral lobe slightly longer than the prolateral lobe.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
